                    <h3>Cromer, Norfolk</h3>

                    <p>
                        Cromer is a lovely seaside town on the north-Norfolk coast. Like Swanage, it's fairly standard
                        for and
                        English beach town and a very pleasant place to spend some time.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        I've stayed rwice at the Caravanning and Motorhome Club campsite which is just outside Cromer (I
                        think the
                        adress is technically East Runton, though it's about halfway between the two on the main road to
                        Sheringham). The site is lovely as and very neat, as expected from on of the big clubs. And
                        despite being
                        the Caravan and Motorhome Club has a tent field with about ten pitches.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        There are several other campsites in the area, including a Camping and Caravanning Club site in
                        West Runton.
                        There are also multiple holiday parks with static caravans. You can walk to some
                        stairs down the cliffs to Cromer beach in about ten minutes, or a further five minutes to the
                        main ramp
                        entryway to the beach by the pier. Alternatively, there's a bus stop right outside the site that
                        goes to
                        Cromer (and on to norwich) in one direction and to Sheringham in the other.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Sheringham is another seaside town about three miles west of Cromer. I would say it's slightly
                        bigger than
                        Cromer and has both a mainline station with connections to norwich (the same train that gets you
                        to Cromer)
                        and a stream train.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        You can walk on the path beside the road to Sheringham from the campsite in about an hour, which
                        is a fairly
                        pleasant walk with sea views for a lot of the way. Alternatively, you can follow the Norfolk
                        Coast path
                        which can be found right outside the campsite and heads to Sheringham and beyond.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Or you could walk down the beach. I did this previously and it was my favourite beach walk I've
                        ever done. I
                        don't know if you can do it at high tide (and since there are huge cliffs and no way off the
                        beach between
                        towns I wouldn't risk it) but at low tide it is an <em>incredibly</em> impressive experience -
                        about three
                        miles just walking on wet compacted sand. And then once you reach Sheringham you can spend some
                        time on the
                        seafront with some fish and chips and then get a bus straight back to the campsite.
                    </p>
                </div>
